<h3><a name="get"> get fim  </a></h3>


<!--Fim aims towards respecting <a href="http://www.gnu.org">GNU</a> coding and documentation standards and conventions. -->

<br> &nbsp;<br>


<br> &nbsp;<br>
<br> &nbsp;<br>
You are welcome to download the latest (prerelease, dated DATE) snapshot of Fim here:
<a href="fim-VERSION.tar.gz">fim-VERSION.tar.gz</a>
<a href="SIG">SIG</a>
( SIZE bytes ). 


<br> &nbsp;<br>
If you want to be sure of downloaded files authenticity, you should _at_least_ follow these steps:
<h6>
<pre>
<br>
wget FWP/TGZ
wget FWP/SIG
gpg --search 'dezperado autistici org'
# import the key from a trusted keyserver by following on screen instructions
gpg --verify SIG
</pre>
</h6>


<br> &nbsp;<br>
The typical sequence of actions to build Fim, which should suffice is :
<h6>
<pre>
<br>
tar xzf fim-VERSION.tar.gz 
cd fim-VERSION 
./configure --help=short 
./configure 
make 
su -c "make install"
</pre>
</h6>


<br> &nbsp;<br>
Of course, there is a lot of
<a href="FIM.html">documentation</a> available
(here the <a href="README.html">README</a> page)
.
You are welcome to <a href="FIM.html#intro">browse</a> it even before downloading Fim.

There are no screenshots of Fim here! Frankly, they would be useless, since Fim runs fullscreen, and the only
thing of note would be a nice textual console on the bottom of the screen. But there is no need for making
screenshots of this :)


<br> &nbsp;<br>
If you are interested at the SVN (subversion) <a href="REPOSITORY">repository</a>,
typing :
<h6>
<pre>
<br>
svn export REPOSITORY
</pre>
</h6>
at the command prompt will download the freshest (possibly unstable) version of Fim in a directory named 'fim'.
